Problem 1 - 2 pts

library(tidyr)
spread_bovids <- spread(bovids, key=site, value=count)

#convert the taxon column to row.names instead, as these will be preserved in the matrix
#that we later use for the analysis
row.names(spread_bovids) <- spread_bovids$taxon
spread_bovids<-spread_bovids[,2:9]

Problem 2 - 2pts

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(aes(x=taxon, y=count, fill=taxon), data=bovids) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  facet_wrap(~site) + 
  theme_bw(30) +

Problem 3 - 2pts

Chi square is a good choice here as all the expected cell frequencies are well above 5. Thus, it can be used to test the hypothesis that row and column variables are associated.

myTest <- chisq.test(spread_bovids)

Just to make sure, lets check that our expected values are high enough.

myTest$expected
##                 site1    site2    site3    site4    site5    site6
## Aepyceros    185.9302 282.9767 292.9535 274.8140 228.2558 256.0698
## Connochaetes 151.7953 231.0251 239.1702 224.3609 186.3504 209.0580
## Gazella      138.3512 210.5637 217.9874 204.4898 169.8457 190.5422
## Tragelaphus  138.9233 211.4344 218.8888 205.3353 170.5481 191.3301
##                 site7    site8
## Aepyceros    141.7907 287.2093
## Connochaetes 115.7594 234.4806
## Gazella      105.5068 213.7132
## Tragelaphus  105.9431 214.5969

Now, we look at the results of the test

myTest
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  spread_bovids
## X-squared = 671.7996, df = 21, p-value < 2.2e-16

There is strong evidence that site and taxon are associated. The null hypothesis is that there is no association between site and taxon. Our p value from the chi square analysis is vanishingly small, which means that data as extreme as ours are extremely unlikely assuming the null hypothesis.
